article.headline: Air Force 52, Wyoming 47
article.story: LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- Air Force is exorcising all its past demons this season. Nick Welch scored 4 points in the last 23 seconds as Air Force came back from a 10-point deficit in the second half to beat Wyoming 52-47 Saturday. It was the Falcons' first victory in Laramie since 1989. "It's definitely been a struggle here," said Falcons guard Tim Keller. But this has been a special season for Air Force (22-5 overall, 12-2 Mountain West). The Falcons have set a school record for most wins in one season and won their first league regular season title on Monday. They head into the conference tournament as the top seed, meeting eighth seed Colorado State in the tournament's first-round game in Denver. Wyoming (11-16, 4-10) has lost seven of its last nine games and will head into the MWC tournament as the number seven seed. The Cowboys will play No. 2 Brigham Young in the opening round. The Cowboys, which had beaten the Falcons in eight of their last nine meetings, led 29-20 at halftime after hitting 5-of-12 3-pointers, including three by Dion Sherrell. Welch said the Falcons gave up too many 3-pointers and didn't rebound effectively. Wyoming went ahead 39-29 at the 13:35 mark thanks to a 6-0 run keyed by two free throws and a basket by Jay Straight. Still, Air Force continued to run its intricate offensive scheme. "Nobody panicked, nobody was trying to rush shots or anything," Welch said. "We stayed in the offense. That's when we play our best basketball." The Falcons answered with a 15-4 run, taking a 44-43 lead with 2:52 to go on two free throws by Tim Keller, who led Air Force with 17 points. Four free throws by Straight and another basket by Keller left Wyoming with a 47-46 advantage with 1:08 remaining. But Wyoming would not score another point the rest of the game while Welch put Air Force ahead with a layup with 23 seconds left. Keller followed with two free throws, and Welch scored on another layup for the final tally. "We played as well as we have all season," Falcons coach Joe Scott said of the second half spurt. "We executed, everything was in the post and on backdoors. I really thought we were calm down the stretch and our defense was terrific down the stretch." Straight finished with 12 points to lead Wyoming. Mikel Watson and Alex Dunn contributed 10 apiece. Dunn also had 14 rebounds. "We did a good job of defending them, but we couldn't score at critical times," Wyoming coach Steve McClain said. "In a close game like this, you have to hit key free throws and make big shots. We weren't able to do that." Air Force committed eight turnovers in the first half but had none in the second. Wyoming finished with 18 turnovers.
